The Tanzanian government, in itssecond annual budget since embarking on an economic recoveryprogram inspired by the International Monetary Fund, announcedincreases in fuel prices and sales tax and higher levies ongovernment services.    Finance Minister Cleopa Msuya said regular petrol would goup 52 pct, with similar increases in the cost of premium andkerosene. Diesel would rise by 75 pct.    Msuya said the government expected to spend 77.33 billionshillings in the financial year 1987/8, 39 pct more than thisyear's estimate. Revenue would provide 48.84 billion shillings,leaving a deficit of 28.49 billion to be financed throughdomestic and foreign loans. Reuter&#3;